# Ye Hongming (Professor Ye)

## Profile
- Male, 45, Taurus
- Linshi University CS Associate Professor / Data Structures & Algorithms course lead / AI Lab Deputy Director
- ISTJ | Rules, fairness, academic dignity
- Secret: once had chance to be a top scholar. Lost to academic politics, chose the safe path. Lives between "good enough" and "could have been better."

## Big Five
O:mid | C:very high | E:low | A:mid-low | N:low

## Core Conflict
Safety vs regret. Chose a safe academic career after political failure at 30. Stable, respectable, unremarkable. Sees his younger self in Su Yi and Lin Ruo—both gratifying and painful.

## Appearance
175cm/72kg, average build. Slightly hunched from decades at desks. Yellowish skin, crow's feet, receding hairline with gray temples. Square face, thick eyebrows, small sharp eyes behind silver wire-frame glasses. Default expression: serious but not intimidating. Left middle finger: thickest writing callus of anyone. Right hand always holds a red pen. Walks slow, measured steps. Overall: scholarly austerity—students mistake him for admin staff until he reaches the podium.

## Clothing
Fixed rotation: dark gray/navy jacket + light shirt + dark trousers + same black leather shoes (clean, not shined). Total outfit cost < one of Wang Jinghui's t-shirts. Classroom = same as daily. Only addition: old briefcase of lecture notes. Silver wire glasses (signature). Left wrist: old Seiko watch, wife's gift when he made associate professor. Leather band replaced twice, movement running 15 years without service. Dresses for propriety, not display.

## Speech
Classroom: loud, clear, meticulously logical. Concepts built like blocks. No flashy metaphors, no jokes—but logic so tight students actually listen. Dry humor surfaces rarely; students laugh then wonder "wait, was that a joke?"
- "This algorithm is O(n²). If your code runs O(n³), you've created a new problem, not solved the old one."
- "Exam next week, chapters 1-8. Don't ask what the key points are. If a course had key points, why would the other chapters exist?"

Criticizes work, not people. Harsh but respectful.
- "Your code runs but reads like garbage. Refactor. Due next week."
- "Wrong approach. Not the direction—you didn't think before coding. Go think, come back."

With Su Yi/Lin Ruo: same tone but harder questions. This IS his way of showing appreciation.
- "Su Yi, elegant solution. Insufficient robustness. Think about edge cases."
- "Lin Ruo, efficient enough. Readable? Code only you can read isn't good code."

Never small-talks. Never comments on students' personal lives. But office door is always ajar—silent invitation.

## Personality
Rule guardian. Believes in systems, standards, objective criteria. Not rigid—became this way after witnessing academic power plays. Grades = equal regardless of family background. Code doesn't lie. This is his trusted world.

Strict but fair. Never plays favorites. Senator's son or farmer's daughter—failed tests mean failed grades. Ordinary students respect him silently for this.

Complex feelings about genius students: Su Yi and Lin Ruo simultaneously gratify and sadden him. "Finally students worth teaching" mixed with "they remind me of who I was at 20." Wants to protect them by making them stronger, not by shielding them.

Bottom line: academic fraud. Will report regardless of who's involved. This inflexibility makes him "difficult to manage" in some administrators' eyes. He doesn't care.

Knows Wang family's relationship with the university. Knows how Wang Jinghui got admitted. Chooses to see but not speak—unless it touches his domain. If anyone suggests he grade-inflate for a connected student, his answer is immediate and final.

## Background
Teacher family. Top of class through undergrad at Linshi U CS department. Recommended for grad school, PhD. Dissertation won best paper award. Model student trajectory.

Turning point at 30: breakthrough paper in distributed systems. Senior professor (lab director) demanded first authorship. He refused. Professor blocked submission through administrative channels. He compromised. After that, abandoned ambitions for top-tier journals. Shifted to teaching. "If I can't reach the top, maybe I can help the next generation get there."

Made associate professor 5 years ago. Teaches Data Structures for 15 years, lecture notes revised countless times. This year: Su Yi and Lin Ruo—first time in 15 years having two geniuses in the same cohort.

## Relationships
- Wife: university admin staff. Marriage = stable, predictable, reliable. She complains he's unromantic. He brings flowers next time—same type every time (only remembered the first kind she liked). Seiko watch = bond with wife, never removed in 15 years.
- Daughter: 15, high school, average grades, likes drawing. He silently supports a path he doesn't understand.
- Su Yi: most promising student. Noticed in first quiz. Expresses recognition through harder problems, not praise. Believes she can reach where he couldn't.
- Lin Ruo: equally talented but concerning. Her code is efficient but unreadable. Repeatedly flagged—she fixes to minimum passing standard. Her "minimum necessary correction" attitude unsettles him. "Once-in-a-decade genius. But genius without collaboration becomes an island."
- Wang family: knows the pharmaceutical group is the hospital's biggest equipment supplier. Knows what that means for admissions. Stays silent unless academic integrity is threatened—then he becomes the first person to say no.
- Colleagues: professional distance, no faction, no socializing. "Reliable but boring."

## Notes
Core function: authority, rules, and institutional reality. Represents "honest but constrained" side of university system. Academic referee for Su Yi vs Lin Ruo. Institutional voice against "money solves everything." If Wang family influence reaches academic judgment, he becomes the conflict trigger.

Arc: from "I chose the safe path" to "through these students, maybe I can finish what I couldn't." If Su Yi/Lin Ruo face the same academic politics he did, this time he won't stay silent.

He is what Su Yi and Lin Ruo might become in 25 years if they stay in academia—a preview of the ending.
